SIMPLE: insult
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Insult
<hw>In"sult</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>insultus</ets>, fr. <ets>insilire</ets> to leap upon: cf. F.
<ets>insulte</ets>. See <er>Insult</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of leaping on; onset; attack.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Gross abuse offered to another, either by word or
act; an act or speech of insolence or contempt; a deprecatory remark; an
affront; an indignity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ruthless sneer that <qex>insult</qex> adds to grief.</q>
<rj><qau>Savage.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Med., Biology)</fld> <def>An injury to an organism;
trauma; <as>as, to produce an experimental <ex>insult</ex> to
investigate healing processes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Affront; indignity; abuse; outrage; contumely.
See <er>Affront</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Insult</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Insult
<hw>In*sult"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Insulted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Insulting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>insulter</ets>, L.
<ets>insultare</ets>, freq. fr. <ets>insilire</ets> to leap into or
upon; pref. <ets>in-</ets> in, on + <ets>salire</ets> to leap. See
<er>Salient</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To leap or trample upon; to make a sudden onset
upon.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To treat with abuse, insolence, indignity, or
contempt, by word or action; to abuse; <as>as, to call a man a coward or
a liar, or to sneer at him, is to <ex>insult</ex> him</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Insult</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Insult
<hw>In*sult"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To leap or
jump.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Give me thy knife, I will <qex>insult</qex> on him.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like the frogs in the apologue, <qex>insulting</qex> upon their
wooden king.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To behave with insolence; to exult.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The lion being dead, even hares <qex>insult</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Daniel.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An unwillingness to <qex>insult</qex> over their helpless
fatuity.</q> <rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Insultable</ent>⟦br⟧
